title: For Sale:  Double Rig Cowboy Holster-Natural Brown: Custom Deluxe Circle KB© Model A1 Double Rig, QuickDraw, CrossDraw Cowboy Holster Rig
postcontent:
Offered for sale is a beautiful Circle KB© custom deluxe Model A1 QuickDraw CrossDraw Double Rig Cowboy Holster (hand cut and tooled contoured A1 QuickDraw Buscadero Gunfighter style gunbelt with one fully attached hand tooled right hand draw dualist holster and one matching hand tooled Mexican Loop style CrossDraw holster looped onto the left side of the gunbelt) –– SIZE 38.   The holsters are sized to fit a pair of Colt SAA 1873 revolvers chambered in .45 LC and having 5 ½ " barrels.  The holsters will nicely accommodate similar style single action revolvers having 4 ¾ " barrels and even the 3 ½ " barrels featured on many Sheriff or Express Rider models without looking like “too much holster” for the gun.  The 18 cartridge loops centered on the back of the gunbelt, as described below, are sized to fit .45 LC cartridges snuggly.  Rounds in calibers smaller than .44 Special (Colt) or .44 mag might wobble in the cartridge loops.  I bought the rig for my own use and wore it very little.  It is in excellent condition and still has that new leather smell!  The holster rig is made from premium Grade A vegetable tanned double shoulder cowhide leather and finished to a hand oiled natural brown color. It is fully lined with soft lining leather, with special metal reinforcement at the cylinder area.  The rig includes beautiful custom hand tooled border decoration in a unique scallop and dot pattern along the upper and lower edges of the gunbelt and repeated in an oblong oval border shape on the front of each holster.  The rig’s hardware consists of clipped Cody style silver buckles on the ornamental holster straps that run across the middle of each holster and a full size frontier style clipped corner smooth silver Cody style main belt buckle.  The beautifully finished and tooled belt is 2.75 inches wide and is hand cut contoured to drop at the right hip, whether worn with the left side CrossDraw holster or as a single right side only holster rig.  The belt has 18 cartridge loops centered in the back of the belt.  The cartridge loops are hand-laced wet (not sewn) and dry molded to fit a .45 LC cartridge size.  The CrossDraw holster is right-handed (positioned on the left hip) and can be easily removed by sliding it down the belt and over the main buckle, to turn the rig into a right handed single rig.  All in all, a beautiful and functional reproduction of American Old-West cowboy “gear”, with a big dose of 1930’s through 1960’s Hollywood thrown in to boot!  It’s an item that any “Cowboy Gun” enthusiast would be pleased to own.

Original retail 2006 - $485.00.  
Price for item offered here, used and as is (superb condition) - $255.00

Terms/Shipping:  Sale is final “as is”.  Purchase price to be paid in full in cash or USPS money order.  Ship to lower 48 US States only.  Shipping via USPS $20 payable by USPS money order in advance along with purchase price.

Info about sizing from Circle KB© website (http://www.circlekb.com/):

For Gun Belt sizes please measure yourself and select the inches at which you will buckle at the center hole of your gun belt. This is an important measurement and is different than your normal pant belt or true waist size. Typically your gun belt size will be 4-5 inches larger than your regular blue jean size or pant belt depending on your gender, confirmation and build.
Remember you will be buckling your gun belt below your normal pant waist, wearing clothing, chaps or winter gear so please take this into consideration when providing your gun belt size measurement. We provide 8 holes spaced one inch apart in the billet providing a 2-3 inch adjustment out and in from center to accommodate different clothing and weight gain or loss.

See Circle KB© website:  http://www.circlekb.com/  for more information and lots of interesting cowboy gun leather and accessories.

Disclaimer:  I have no affiliation with Circle KB©.  I like their products and service and I think you will too

title: For Sale/Trade:  COLT police positive 38-200 1941
location: Rock Hill, Rock Hill, South Carolina
postcontent: Fine condition WWII era Colt Police Positive revolver that was sold to Britian early in the war and is in the .38-200 caliber (.38 S&W). About 49,000 total guns were made 1940-41 and this example is a very early gun that has the Crowned W proof on the left side of the frame and is stamped serial number #15222 on the butt. These crowned W guns were sold prior to the Lend-Lease agreement and are much scarcer with only about 18,000 guns in that contract. This classic gun has a standard 5" barrel with a fine, bright bore that has strong rifling. Action is smooth with a tight lockup, pistol shows little use. Frame and yoke have matching assembly numbers and pommel has original lanyard loop. Metal finish is a factory original blue with a little holster wear and fading. Original checkered wood grips have the Colt medallion on each side with a tight fit and no cracks. A scarce and desirable WWII Colt revolver that will make a fine addition to a collection and a great display.

title: For Sale:  Double Rig Cowboy Holster-Black: Custom Deluxe Circle KB© Marshall Model Double Rig, StraightDraw Cowboy Holster Rig
location: North Metro - Auburn Hills, Detroit, Michigan
postcontent:
Offered for sale is a beautiful Circle KB© custom deluxe Marshall Model Double Rig Cowboy Holster (two Mexican Loop style Marshall Model holsters looped onto the right and left sides of the Marshall Model gunbelt)  – SIZE 38.  The holsters are sized to fit a pair of USFA Reproduction Colt SAA 1873 revolvers chambered in .45 LC and having 7 ½ " barrels.  The holsters will nicely accommodate similar style single action revolvers having 5 ½ " and even 4 ¾ " barrels without looking like “too much holster” for the gun.  The 18 cartridge loops centered on the back of the gunbelt, as described below, are sized to fit .45 LC cartridges snuggly.  Rounds in calibers smaller than .44 Special (Colt) or .44 Mag might wobble in the cartridge loops.  I bought the rig for my own use and wore it very little.  It is in excellent condition and still has that new leather smell!  There are some minor scuff marks on the tongue piece of the 3 piece silver buckle set.  The blemishes are from running the tongue piece through the silver stay while buckling or unbuckling the belt.  The marks rub out with a chamois or soft cloth and some silver polish or auto wax.  I’ve done it before.  The holster rig is made from top-grade double shoulder vegetable tanned cowhide and finished to a hand dyed deep black color. It is fully lined with soft lining leather, with special metal reinforcement at the cylinder area.  Hand tooled into the face side of each of the rig’s two holsters is a rich Basketweave pattern, which is embellished further with Circle KB©’s special Santa Fe style border pattern that is hand tooled into each holster as a border surrounding the Basketweave field tooled into the holsters.  This pattern is also hand tooled into the top and bottom edges of the 2"wide leather accent straps that go across the middle of each holster.  Each of these holster straps are also decorated with one 3/4" silver concho affixed to the center of each strap (see hardware description below).  The Santa Fe style border pattern is also hand tooled into the top and bottom edges of the rig’s 2 ¾ " wide gun belt.  Tooling the Santa Fe style border pattern takes 6 marks per 3/4" and creates an outstanding finish.  The rig’s hardware includes an elegant silver Rope Edge 3-piece buckle set (on a 1 ½" belt buckle strap attached to the 2 ¾ " wide gun belt).  The hardware also includes 4 round silver High Sierra, Rope Edge pattern conchos.  Two of the conchos are ¾ " diameter and are placed in the center of the 2" wide leather accent strap going across the middle of both of the 2 holsters.  The other two conchos are each 1 ½ " in diameter and are placed in the middle of the gun belt flanking each side of the row of cartridge loops located in the middle of the back side of the gunbelt.  The belt has 18 cartridge loops centered in the back of the belt.  The cartridge loops are hand-laced wet (not sewn) and dry molded to fit a .45 LC cartridge size.  The rig can easily be converted to either a right or left hand single rig by sliding either of the holsters down to the nearest end of the gun belt and slipping it over the buckle.  All in all, a beautiful and functional reproduction of American Old-West cowboy “gear”, with a big dose of 1930’s through 1960’s Hollywood thrown in to boot!  It’s an item that any “Cowboy Gun” enthusiast would be pleased to own.

Original retail 2006 - $580.00  
Price for item offered here, used and as is (superb condition) - $295.00

Terms/Shipping:  Sale is final “as is”.  Purchase price to be paid in full in cash or USPS money order.  Ship to lower 48 US States only.  Shipping via USPS $20 payable by USPS money order in advance along with purchase price.

Info about sizing from Circle KB© website (http://www.circlekb.com/):

For Gun Belt sizes please measure yourself and select the inches at which you will buckle at the center hole of your gun belt. This is an important measurement and is different than your normal pant belt or true waist size. Typically your gun belt size will be 4-5 inches larger than your regular blue jean size or pant belt depending on your gender, confirmation and build.
Remember you will be buckling your gun belt below your normal pant waist, wearing clothing, chaps or winter gear so please take this into consideration when providing your gun belt size measurement. We provide 8 holes spaced one inch apart in the billet providing a 2-3 inch adjustment out and in from center to accommodate different clothing and weight gain or loss.

If you're looking for a serious combat pistol loaded with features, you just found it.

title: For Sale:  French MAS 49 (not 49/56) - MINT Unfired Condition
postcontent:
This is a MAS Model 1949 rifle that is unfired. The rifle is in 100% condition and shows no handling/storage marks.

I purchased this rifle from a collector friend over 23 years ago and have had it safely stored ever since.

Far fewer MAS 49 semi-auto long rifles were made as compared to the more common 49/56 carbine. My research shows that 20,600 Model 1949 rifles were made while over 275,000 of the 49/56 were produced. This rifle is a true collectors piece and it's sure to continue to increase in value. 

Rifle comes with all the factory accessories that were originally shipped with it. There are two heavy poly bags of equipment - the first has cleaning kit, tools, sling, pouches, spare parts, & operating manual (in French). Then the second bag has (4) 10 round magazines that are packed in oil. Both bags are factory sealed and have never been opened. There is also five original boxes of French 7.5mm ball ammo. This ammo is brass case, bright & shiny so I know it would shoot just fine, however it's collectible by itself so I'd suggest buying some new production ammo from PPU or S&B if you intend to shoot this rifle.  

I'm asking $1050. Rifle is local sale only (no shipping) with pickup in the Brandon area by a Florida resident that is at least 21 years old. A bill of sale will be furnished.

I would consider the following .22 rifles as a partial trade: SIG 522, Beretta ARX, ISSC MK-22, or GSG STG44-22.


Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Nikon D90 with lots of extras
postcontent:
I have a D90 in excellent shape that only has 6,127 shutter actuations that I'm looking to sell.  I bought the camera body new in September of 2010 and it was my primary camera until I bought my D7000 about a year and half ago, I kept the D90 around for a back up and it handled the job very well, picture quality between the two is hard to see without pixel counting.  The main reason I upgraded was for the two SD slots on the 7000...and just to upgrade of course...lol.  Honestly there is no real reason I can give for upgrading, the D90 performs just as good as the "newer" models, image quality will be a very minimal improvement with the new entry level D3XXX or D5XXX...The D90 is still faster than these though.  You really won't make a huge leap in quality until you go to the newest "prosumer" models like the D7XXX and the like.  

All lenses were purchased separately over the last few years for either mine or my wife's cameras and have always been fitted with lens filters.  When not in use/in storage they have always had both caps installed.  Each piece was purchased brand new by me and has been taken care of very well.  The entire package looks and performs like new with the exception of the plastic cover that protects the rear LCD, it has minor scratches from use, the LCD however is flawless.

title: For Sale:  FOR SALE/TRADE: REMINGTON 788 .308 Rifle
postcontent:
Nice and accurate .308 has a three round detachable magazine and a wooden Monte Carlo stock. Already has scope mount.   Manufactured in 1969

The Model 788 is famous for its accuracy and has been dubbed by many throughout its history to be a "tackdriver."

Interested in Cash or Trade.  Would like Glock, Sig, Ruger, or ? make a proposal.

I have a Tasco 3x9 scope I can included if necessary to make up the difference on a trade.  Call REDACTED

About the Remington Model 788 (From Wikipedia): http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Remington_788
The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles. The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs.
The second distinguishing feature is the receiver. It has a smaller ejection port than similar bolt action rifles, and no bolt lug raceways. The single stack magazine design yields a smaller feed opening in the bottom of the receiver compared to rifles using a double stack magazine well. When machining of these smaller ports is complete there is more steel remaining in the receiver between the ejection port and adjacent feed port, and significantly more steel overall where all receivers have the least strength. These characteristics combined to make the Remington 788 receiver more rigid and stronger than most, if not all, competing designs, including the Remington 700 which shares the same outside receiver diameter. A rifle's accuracy tends to increase slightly as the rigidity of the receiver increases, as this slightly reduces barrel deflection during firing. Thus the Remington 788 has the structural foundation to be a very accurate rifle.
